<font color="#FF0000">SOURCES &amp; FACTS</font><br>
<tt>Sat Feb  1 16:38:37 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
OK, here's Marilyn Young's sources for her high suicide figures (&quot;at least sixty-thousand&quot;):  Tamar Lewin, &quot;Nations's Homeless Veterans Battle a New Foe: Defeatism&quot;, The New York Times, December 30, 1987;  Myra MacPherson, &quot;Long Time Passing:  Vietnam and the Haunted Generation&quot;, Garden City, NY., Doubleday, 1984, p. 185.  I'll check out the NY Times at our library when I get a chance.  The other one I've never read, though I've heard of it.  Anybody know about it?<br><br>
I don't mind the particular bias of an author, as long as he/she is up front about it.  After all, who isn't &quot;anti-war&quot;?  I also agree that the facts are beyond dispute, if we can all agree on what the facts are.  I do feel there is more to this than the facts, though, and that good histories go beyond the facts.  That's one reason why I like &quot;Fire in the Lake&quot;.  Dangerous ground, I know, but vital if we are to truly understand what happened.<br><br>
Thanks for the sources, Joe.  I do have the VFW chronology.  The others are new to me and I'll see if I can get them.  I have a couple of &quot;picture book&quot; type choronologies that I picked up used at some book warehouse sale.  One is called &quot;The Vietnam War - Day by Day&quot;.  Can't recall the other, off hand.  I'll look it up.
